<dl id="n05026c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05026c">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05026c"> 26(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> jeans / washing limericks / Berlins ) gloves</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05026c"><li>FW 36.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n05026c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n05026c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n05026c">MS BL 47471b-1</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:025 <a name="b20d" href="../../FF/fdra/bda.htm#b20d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/b20d.htm#n05026c">Draft: I.2&sect;2.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><i>Jac.</i> To be sure I does&mdash;down as a hammer! When I wants to find out whether a chap&apos;s a real gen&apos;lemn I looks at his boots, and I&apos;m generally fly; but if so be I has my doubts, I looks at his <mark>gloves</mark>, and then I&apos;m wide awake. Many sports <mark>Berlins</mark>&mdash;or policemen&apos;s, as I calls &apos;em, &apos;cos the blues wears &apos;em&mdash;others comes the artful dodge of <mark>jeans and washing Limericks</mark>&mdash;(them does werry well for barbers&apos; clerks, and sich like)&mdash;but the real genlemn sports kids; not big shilling ones made of sheepskin, but three-and-six-penny straws or lavenders: them&apos;s the ticket, and there&apos;s no mistake about them. The swells may come the tailor&apos;s toggery, but they ayn&apos;t got the taste to come the genlemn at the &apos;stremity of the toes and fingers. <small> Charles Selby, <a name="BOOTS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BOOTS"><cite title="source">The Boots at the Swan</cite></a>, (ca 1875) 7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Only the word &lsquo;Berlins&rsquo; is crossed through. &lsquo;Berlins&rsquo;, short for Berlin gloves, are a knitted glove (of Berlin wool). </mm> </dd></dl>
